ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[This is an interesting epidemiological niche for a ubiquitous
organism that has been known for a long time to be capable of causing
cutaneous and other infections in humans. Postsurgical or accidental
wound infections are common presentations. The current popularity of
nail salons is likely to result in other outbreaks as noted above. _M.
fortuitum_ and _M. chelonae_ are both rapid-growers (produce visible
colonies in 2-5 days on specialized media) among the mycobacteria, and
are often considered together as the _M. fortuitum-chelonae_ complex.
Both strains can cause cutaneous infections, but they produce
morphologically distinguishable colonies, _M. fortuitum_ producing
more filamentous extensions. - Mod.ES
